ism: The Feminist Dimension of Rosa Luxemburg’s Intellectual Leadership -- tPart III. Women and Political Power in the Twentieth and Twenty-First Centuries -- t11: Follow-the-Leader: Tracing Male Influence on Leni Riefenstahl’s Triumph des Willens -- t12: “Leaning In”: The Career Woman as Instrument of Neoliberal Critique -- t13: Change, Persistence, and Contradiction: The Representation of Female Political Leadership in Gendered Media -- t14: Petra Kelly: A Green Leader out of Place? -- t15: “Mama Merkel” and “Mutti-Multikulti”: The Perils of Governing While Female -- t16: Women Leaders in Troubled Times: The Leadership Styles of Angela Merkel and Hillary Clinton -- tBibliography -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA collection of essays achieving a deeper understanding of the historical roots and theoretical assumptions that inform the realities and fantasies of German female leadership.The Western tradition of excluding women from leadership and disparaging their ability to lead has persisted for centuries, not least in Germany. Even today, resistance to women holding power is embedded in literary, cultural, andhistorical values that presume a fundamental opposition between the adjective "female" and the substantive "leader." Women who do achieve positions of leadership are faced with a panoply of prejudicial misconceptions: either considered incapable of leadership (conceived of as alpha-male behavior), or pigeonholed as suited only to particular forms of leadership (nurturing, cooperative, egalitarian, communicative, etc.). Focusing on the German-speakingcountries, this volume works to dismantle the prevailing disassociation of women and leadership across a range of disciplines. Contributions discuss literary works involving women's political authority and cultivation of community from Maria Antonia of Saxony to Elfriede Jelinek; women's social activism, as embodied by figures from Hedwig Dohm to Rosa Luxemburg; women in political film, environmentalism, neoliberalism, and the media from Leni Riefenstahlto Petra Kelly to Maren Ade; and political leaders Hillary Clinton and Angela Merkel. Contributors: Dorothee Beck, Seth Berk, Friederike Brühöfener, Margaretmary Daley, Aude Defurne, Helga Druxes, Sarah Vandegrift Eldridge, Anke Gilleir, Rachel J. Halverson, Peter Hudis, Elisabeth Krimmer, Stephen Milder, Joyce Marie Mushaben, Lauren Nossett, Patricia Anne Simpson, Almut Spalding, Inge Stephan, Lisa Fetheringill Zwicker. Elisabeth Krimmer is Professor of German at the University of California, Davis. Patricia Anne Simpson is Professor of German at the University of Nebraska-Lincoln.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLeadership in womenzGermanyxHistory. 0aPolitical leadershipzGermanyxHistory. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzGermanyxHistory. 4aGerman History. 4aGerman Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aAngela Merkel.  aElfriede Jelinek.  aEnvironmentalism.  aGermany.  aHedwig Dohm.  aHillary Clinton.  aLeni Riefenstahl.  aMaren Ade.  aMaria Antonia of Saxony.  aNeoliberalism.  aPetra Kelly.  aPolitical Film.  aRosa Luxemburg.  aWomen's Social Activism.1 aAlmut Spalding, Almut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeck, Dorothee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerk, Seth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrühöfener, Friederike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaley, Margaretmary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDefurne, Aude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDruxes, H